[The Dutch notification requirement seems to have been prolific; the Belgian accumulated information is based upon voluntary reporting, thus the true numbers of congenital malformations and their geographic distribution may somewhat differ. The absence of positive test results in cattle, in both countries, is waiting for clarification.

So far, no information on the occurrence of congenital malformations in ruminants has become available from Germany, besides a piece of information (from a Dutch source) on a single positive case in cattle (foetus?). Such information will be appreciated.

Though SBV has not been reported previously in Europe or elsewhere, 2 other teratogenic orthobunyaviruses, Akabane and (to a lesser extent) Aino, have been reported since the 70's in the Eastern Mediterranean region.

The Netherland official report to the OIE "Event summary: Schmallenberg disease, Netherlands" on 39 outbreaks of an emerging disease, including a map, was submitted on 5 Jan 2012 and is available at http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=11447. - Mod.AS.]
